\begin_layout Quote

\shape slanted
Why Hartree-Fock? The parametrisation of the pseodo-potential is based on
 the results of a HF- calculation results obtained for a CH3● radical and
 C2H4 molecule.
 Systems of this size (i.e.
 10 and 16 electrons, respecively) can be efficiently treated at a correlated
 level of theory such as MP2 or coupled- cluster theory (RIMP2 and RI-CC2
 in case of TURBOMOLE), so the authors have to explain why the Hartree-Fock
 methods was their method of choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider Hartree-Fock as method of choice for extraction of our pseudopotenti
als as it is unbiased in terms of electronic correlation.
 On top of it, one can add electronic correlation with any method (DFT,
 CI, etc.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\shape slanted
Why not B3LYP? This work compares the results obtained using the pseudo-potentia
l model to DFT calculations of the rather popular PBE and PBE0 functionals,
 in addition to the comparably rarely employed TPSS and TPSSh functionals.
 Although the suitability of the B3LYP functional is (rightly) the focus
 of continuing debates in the literature, it still represents one of the
 most influential developments in theoretical/computational chemistry, and
 cannot be ignored.
 For this reason, the authors should also compare to results obtained using
 this method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The choice of functionals that we use in this work comes from the idea to
 climb Jacob's ladder in the most systematic manner possible.
 PBE and PBE0 differ only by the inclusion of exact exchange whereas there
 is no pure functional that can be directly associated with B3LYP.
 Hence this choice.
\end_layout

